{"title":"Mario Kart World’s $80 price isn’t that high, historically","link":"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2025/04/will-mario-kart-worlds-80-price-become-gamings-new-normal/","date":1744147582000,"content":"<p>Last week, Nintendo made waves across the game industry by announcing that <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2025/04/psa-mario-kart-world-is-50-bundled-with-a-switch-2-but-80-by-itself/\"><em>Mario Kart World</em> would sell for a suggested price of $80</a> in the US. That nominal price represents a new high-water mark both for Nintendo and for the game industry at large, which has generally reserved prices above $70 for <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2009/11/worth-the-money-the-gaming-collectors-edition-trend/\">fancy, trinket-laden collectors' editions</a> or <a href=\"https://store.ubisoft.com/us/assassins-creed-shadows-digital-deluxe-edition/673b49019baa3f5f7f025a29.html?lang=en_US\">Digital Deluxe Editions</a> that include all variety of downloadable bonuses.</p>\n<figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.001.png\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.001.png 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.001-640x480.png 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.001-768x576.png 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.001-980x735.png 980w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      Console gaming's nominal price ceiling has gone up pretty consistently in the last 40+ years.\n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Kyle Orland / Ars Technica\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.002.png\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.002.png 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.002-640x480.png 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.002-768x576.png 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/gameprices2025.002-980x735.png 980w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      After adjusting for inflation, an $80 price level doesn't seem all that out of the ordinary.\n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Kyle Orland / Ars Technica\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n  \n<p>When you adjust historical game prices for inflation, though, you find that asking $80 for a baseline game in 2025 is broadly in line with the prices big games were commanding 10 to 15 years ago. And given the <a href=\"https://www.brookings.edu/articles/what-caused-the-u-s-pandemic-era-inflation/\">faster-than-normal inflation rates of the last five years</a>, even the $70 nominal game prices that <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/07/will-nba-2k21s-70-price-set-a-new-next-gen-console-standard/\">set a new standard in 2020</a> don't have the same purchasing oomph they once did.</p>\n<h2>The data</h2>\n<figure>\n      <img width=\"640\" height=\"868\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1983gp-640x868.jpg\" alt=\"A yellowed print advertisement for video game cartridges.\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1983gp-640x868.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1983gp-300x407.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1983gp.jpg 737w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      $34.99 for <em>Centipede</em> on the Atari 2600 might sound cheap, but that 1983 price is the equivalent of roughly $90 today.\n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n                      <a href=\"https://www.retrowaste.com/wp-content/gallery/1980s-video-games-ads/1983-atari-catridges-games-02.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">\n          \n          Retro Waste\n\n                      </a>\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"640\" height=\"868\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1988gp-640x868.jpg\" alt=\"A yellowed print advertisement for home video game consoles and accessories.\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1988gp-640x868.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1988gp-300x407.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1988gp-768x1041.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1988gp-1133x1536.jpg 1133w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1988gp-980x1328.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1988gp.jpg 1212w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      Check out the premium pricing for <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/tag/zelda/\"><em>Zelda</em></a> titles above other NES games in the 1988 Sears catalog.\n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n                      <a href=\"https://www.huguesjohnson.com/features/sears_catalog/sears-catalog-1988-pg615-NES_full.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">\n          \n          Hughes Johnson\n\n                      </a>\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"640\" height=\"870\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1993gp-640x870.jpg\" alt=\"A 1990s advertisement for home video game consoles and accessories.\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1993gp-640x870.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1993gp-300x408.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1993gp-768x1044.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1993gp-980x1332.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/1993gp.jpg 1024w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      If you wanted <em>Streets of Rage 2</em> from Electronics Boutique in 1993, you'd better have been ready to pay extra.\n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n                      <a href=\"https://www.huguesjohnson.com/scans/ebspring93/EBSpring93_04_Genesis.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">\n          \n          Hughes Johnson\n\n                      </a>\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n  \n<p>To judge <em>Mario Kart World</em>'s $80 price against historical trends, we first needed to figure out how much games cost in the past. To do that, we <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/07/the-return-of-the-70-video-game-has-been-a-long-time-coming/\">built off of our similar 2020 analysis</a>, which relied on <a href=\"https://www.retrowaste.com/wp-content/gallery/1980s-video-games-ads/\">scanned catalogs</a> and <a href=\"https://www.retrowaste.com/wp-content/gallery/1990s-video-games-ads/\">retail advertising fliers</a> for real examples of nominal console game pricing going back to the Atari era. For more recent years, we relied more on <a href=\"https://kotaku.com/microsoft-to-sell-next-gen-games-for-60-price-of-gami-513489951\">press reports</a> and <a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20201202032750/https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/store/top-paid/games/xbox\">archived digital storefronts</a> to show what prices new games were actually selling for at the time.</p><p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2025/04/will-mario-kart-worlds-80-price-become-gamings-new-normal/\">Read full article</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2025/04/will-mario-kart-worlds-80-price-become-gamings-new-normal/#comments\">Comments</a></p>","author":"Kyle Orland","siteTitle":"Ars Technica","siteHash":"5b0ddf6e8923e49262a7894cfd77962733e43fbcc565a103b48373820b310636","entryHash":"76bd787f2f2a9624d641b9ca5213554812b7598fe2138b476510220ce17eb835","category":"Tech"}